  = section "Diminutives and Augmentatives" do
    %p Diminutives and augmentatives are emotive derivations, typically expressing affection or endearment in addition to their more basic functions of smallness or largeness. Tunisian diminutives tend to be quite common in casual discourse, and may be freely applied to both common nouns and personal names.
    %p Note that unlike in other Romance languages, the diminutive and augmentative suffixes do not vary by gender, but rather assign it (with diminutives always being feminine and augmentatives always being masculine). Thus, while <i>fil</i> /ˈfil/ “boy” is masculine, its diminutive form <i>fiote</i> /ˈfiw.tə/ “little boy” is feminine; conversely, <i>faile</i> /ˈfaj.lə/ “girl” is feminine, but its augmentative <i>failâ</i> /faj.ˈlaː/ “big girl” is masculine.

    = section "Diminutives" do
      %p The primary means of forming diminutives is with the suffix <i>-te</i> /tə/ added to the noun stem, replacing any vowel /ə/ if present. It has a number of variations depending on the shape of the noun stem.
      %p The most basic form, <i>-te</i>, is used when the noun stem ends in a single consonant: <i>ymic</i> “friend” → <i>ymicte</i> [ˈi.mik.tə], <i>cai</i> “dog” → <i>caite</i> [ˈkaj.tə].
      %p The augmented forms <i>-ite</i> /ˈitə/ or <i>-éte</i> /ˈe.tə/ are typically used if the stem ends in /t/, /d/, or /r/: <i>Petr</i> “Peter” → <i>Pétréte</i> [pe.ˈtre.tə], <i>Marie</i> “Maria” → <i>Marite</i> [mʌ.ˈri.tə], <i>cât</i> “cat” → <i>câtite</i> [kʌ.ˈti.tə].
      %p When the stem ends in a long vowel or /n/, it shortens and diphthongizes before <i>-te</i>: <i>sô</i> “sister” → <i>soite</i> [ˈsoj.tə], <i>pûlgane</i> “orange” → <i>pûlgaite</i> [ˈpuːl.gaj.tə].
      %p When the stem ends in /m/, it transforms to /p/ before <i>-te</i>: <i>dom</i> “house” → <i>dopte</i> [ˈdop.tə], <i>cinéme</i> “movie theater” → <i>cinépte</i>.
      %p When the stem ends in /l/, it will often lenite to /w/, forming a diphthong: <i>Nicole</i> “Nicole” → <i>Nicoute</i> [ni.ˈkow.tə], <i>fil</i> “boy” → <i>fiote</i> [ˈfiw.tə].
      %p When the stem ends in the sequence -ViC- (i.e., a diphthong in /j/ followed by a consonant), the /i/ will often metathesize and reappear between the stem and diminutive suffix: <i>faile</i> “girl” → <i>falite</i> [fʌ.ˈli.tə], <i>caif</i> “mood” → <i>cafite</i> [kʌ.ˈfi.tə].
      %p When the stem ends in some other consonant cluster, it is common for one or more consonants to be lost before <i>-te</i> is added: <i>pesc</i> “fish” → <i>péste</i> [ˈpɛs.tə], <i>rost</i> “mouth” → <i>rosite</i> [rɔ.ˈsi.tə].

    = section "Augmentatives" do
      %p Tunisian augmentatives are formed by suffixing an echo vowel to the noun stem. This vowel is always long, and its quality depends on the last non-reduced vowel in stem: <i>-â</i> for /a/, <i>-ê</i> for /i e/, and <i>-ô</i> for /u o/, with diphthongs acting occurred to their nucleus. This suffix is always stressed: <i>fil</i> [ˈfil] “boy” → <i>filê</i> [fi.ˈleə], <i>faile</i> [ˈfaj.lə] “girl” → <i>failâ</i> [faj.ˈlaː], <i>cât</i> [ˈkaːt] “cat” → <i>câtâ</i> [kʌ.ˈtaː], <i>cai</i> [ˈkaj] “dog” → <i>canâ</i> [kʌ.ˈnaː].
      %p Augmentatives do not have the pejorative connotation they tend to in other Romance languages. In fact, when applied to people, the augmentative sense has been almost entirely bleached (in much the same way diminutives applied to people do not indicate physical smallness).

%section.footnotes
  = footnote do
    Note that the distribution of Tunisian <i>-iâ</i> and <i>-is</i> does not match up completely with English <i>-ian</i> and <i>-ese</i>, although they are quite close. Note, for instance, <i>sħêniâ</i> “Chinese” or <i>aiglis</i> “English”.
  = footnote do
    However, this <i>cal</i> element can be seen in a number of interrogatives, such as <i>calom</i> “who?” and <i>caltemp</i> “when?”.
  = footnote do
    In Romanian, the original Latin infinitive was reinterpreted as a true noun, while an innovative ‘short’ infinitive took over the role of the non-finite verb form: <i>vedere</i> “sight” from Latin <i>vidēre</i> “to see”, with the new infinitive <i>[a] vedea</i> “to see”. In the Tunisian case, the reinterpretation of the infinitive as a noun was likely under the influence of Semitic and Berber languages, which lack an infinitive in the typical Romance sense, but do have simple nominalizations.
  = footnote do
    However, Tunisian infinitives do retain a few distinctly verbal characteristics as well, such as the ability to take direct objects, adverbial modifiers, and limited passivization. These behaviors will be discussed later in this grammar.
